## GitHub Actions: 58. Workflow Cancellation Strategy

**Workflow Cancellation Strategy** means automatically stopping old or unnecessary workflow runs.

This is useful when new code is pushed while an old workflow is still running.

## Why use cancellation strategy?

✅ Saves GitHub Actions minutes
✅ Avoids duplicate builds
✅ Runs only latest code
✅ Reduces waiting time
✅ Prevents unnecessary deployments

## Main Method: `concurrency`

```yaml
concurrency:
  group: build-${{ github.ref }}
  cancel-in-progress: true
```

## Example: Cancel Old Build When New Push Happens

```yaml
name: Build Cancellation Strategy

on:
  push:
    branches: [ main ]

concurrency:
  group: build-main
  cancel-in-progress: true

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - name: Checkout Code
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Build Application
        run: mvn clean install
```

## Explanation

If one build is already running and another push happens:

```text
Old workflow run → cancelled
New workflow run → starts
```

So GitHub Actions runs only the latest workflow.

## Branch-Based Cancellation Example

```yaml
name: Branch Based Cancellation

on: push

concurrency:
  group: build-${{ github.ref }}
  cancel-in-progress: true

jobs:
  test:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - name: Run Tests
        run: mvn test
```

## Explanation Sentence

Here, workflows are cancelled only for the same branch.
Example: a new push to `main` cancels old `main` workflow, but it will not cancel a workflow running on `dev`.

## Deployment Cancellation Strategy

For production deployment, we usually do **not** cancel running deployment.

```yaml
name: Production Deploy

on:
  push:
    branches: [ main ]

concurrency:
  group: production-deploy
  cancel-in-progress: false

jobs:
  deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - name: Deploy Production
        run: echo "Deploying safely..."
```

## Explanation

```yaml
cancel-in-progress: false
```

Means new deployment waits until the current deployment finishes.

This is safer for production.

## Real-Time Use Case

A developer pushes code 3 times quickly:

```text
Push 1 → workflow started
Push 2 → old workflow cancelled
Push 3 → previous workflow cancelled
```

Only the latest workflow continues.

## Best Practices

Use `cancel-in-progress: true` for build and test workflows.
Use `cancel-in-progress: false` for production deployment.
Use branch-based groups like `${{ github.ref }}`.
Do not cancel critical release workflows.
Keep concurrency group names clear.

## Simple Definition

**Workflow Cancellation Strategy means cancelling old running workflows automatically so only the latest or safest workflow run continues.**
